<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-most-repeated-ssc-cgl-quantitative-aptitude-questions"><span class="ez-toc-section" id="Most_Repeated_SSC_CGL_Quantitative_Aptitude_Questions"></span>Most Repeated SSC CGL Quantitative Aptitude Questions<span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2>



<p>For SSC CGL Tier 2 preparation, the SSC CGL quantitative aptitude questions are very important. Many topics are repeated every year with slight changes. By practicing the SSC CGL quant practice questions and reviewing SSC CGL quantitative aptitude previous year questions, common patterns can be easily found. Below is a list of the most repeated quant questions from Arithmetic and Advanced Mathematics for <a href="https://www.oliveboard.in/ssc-cgl-notification/?ref=contmk-blog-mrscmq" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">SSC CGL Exam</a>.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-table"><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Section</strong></td><td><strong>Topics</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>Arithmetic</strong></td><td>Time and Work &#8211; efficiency, combined work, work left undone</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Time, Speed and Distance &#8211; trains, boats, relative speed</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Percentage, Profit &amp; Loss &#8211; discounts, marked price, selling price</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Simple &amp; Compound Interest &#8211; SI vs CI for 2 years</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Ratio &amp; Proportion &#8211; ages, partnerships, distribution</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Mixture &amp; Alligation &#8211; ratio for mixing solutions or prices</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Averages &#8211; weighted averages, change in group average</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Number System &amp; HCF/LCM &#8211; unit digit, divisibility, least/greatest num</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Advanced Maths</strong></td><td>Algebra &#8211; factorization, identities, quadratic equations</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Geometry &#8211; circles, triangles, quadrilaterals</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Mensuration &#8211; area &amp; volume of 2D and 3D figures</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Trigonometry &#8211; identities, complementary angles, heights &amp; distances</td></tr><tr><td></td><td>Data Interpretation &#8211; tables, bar graphs, pie charts, ratios, percentage</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-how-to-prepare-for-ssc-cgl-quantitative-aptitude"><span class="ez-toc-section" id="How_to_Prepare_for_SSC_CGL_Quantitative_Aptitude"></span>How to Prepare for SSC CGL Quantitative Aptitude?<span class="ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2>



<p>To score well in SSC CGL Quantitative Aptitude, you need a clear plan. Focus on practicing previous questions, learning formulas, and improving speed and accuracy. A good S<a href="https://www.oliveboard.in/ssc-cgl-preparation-strategy/?ref=contmk-blog-mrscmq" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">SC CGL Preparation Strategy</a> helps you solve both basic and tough problems quickly.</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Solve at least 20–30 questions daily from high-frequency topics like Time &amp; Work, Ratio, and Percentage.</li>



<li>Memorize shortcut formulas for Simple &amp; Compound Interest, Profit &amp; Loss, and Averages, and apply them in practice.</li>



<li>Time yourself while solving previous year <strong>SSC CGL quantitative aptitude question papers</strong> to improve speed under exam conditions.</li>



<li>Check each answer carefully to avoid mistakes that could lead to negative marking.</li>



<li>Focus extra practice on Algebra, Geometry, and Data Interpretation sets, as these appear frequently in Tier 2 papers.</li>



<li>Maintain a separate notebook with formulas, key shortcuts, and tricky problem-solving methods for quick revision.</li>



<li>Attempt at least one full-length timed mock test every week to track improvement in speed and accuracy.</li>



<li>Analyze mistakes after each practice session and revise the weak topics immediately.</li>
</ul>



